# Debounce Function

A debounce function delays the execution of a function until after a specified time has passed since it was last called, useful for optimizing performance on frequent events.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => func(...args), delay);
  };
}

// Example: Search input that calls an API
const searchAPI = (query) => console.log(`Searching for: ${query}`);
const debouncedSearch = debounce(searchAPI, 500);

const input = document.querySelector('input');
input.addEventListener('input', (e) => debouncedSearch(e.target.value));
// Only calls searchAPI 500ms after the user stops typing
```

In this example, the `searchAPI` function won't be called until the user stops typing for 500 milliseconds, preventing excessive API requests.
